SIMPLE: fourchette
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fourchette
<hw>Four`chette"</hw> <pr>(f⟦oomac⟧r`sh⟦ecr⟧t")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F., dim. of <ets>fourche</ets>. See <er>Fork</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A table fork.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A small fold of
membrane, connecting the labia in the posterior part of the vulva.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The wishbone or furculum of birds.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>The frog of the hoof of the horse and allied animals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>An instrument used to raise and
support the tongue during the cutting of the fr⟦ae⟧num.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Glove Making)</fld> <def>The forked piece between
two adjacent fingers, to which the front and back portions are
sewed.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>The combination of the
card immediately above and the one immediately below a given
card.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Four-cornered</ent>⟦br⟧
